05121nam a2200805Ia 9783110753028DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107530287 a10.1515/97831107530282doi  a(DE-B1597)584731  a(OCoLC)1396608054  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aSOC0480002bisacsh0484pa297qDE-1011 aVan Den Bossche, Gowaart, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiterary Spectacles of Sultanship :bHistoriography, the Chancery, and Social Practice in Late Medieval Egypt /cGowaart Van Den Bossche. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (IX, 231 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIslam – Thought, Culture, and Society ,x2628-4286 ;v10  aDissertationcGhent Universityd2019.00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tNote on transliteration and abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The sīra corpus: Authors and texts -- tChapter 2 The discourse of Sīra: Historiography, memory, and performance -- tChapter 3 Sīra as an act of narrative construction -- tChapter 4 Sīra as chancery practice: Composition and compilation -- tChapter 5 Sīra as literary communication -- tChapter 6 Sīra as courtly phenomenon -- tChapter 7 Final conclusions -- tBibliography -- tAppendix -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe so-called Mamluk sultans who ruled Egypt and Syria between the late thirteenth and early sixteenth centuries AD have often been portrayed as lacking in legitimacy due to their background as slave soldiers. Sultanic biographies written by chancery officials in the early period of the sultanate have been read as part of an effort of these sultans to legitimise their position on the throne. This book reconsiders the main corpus of six such biographies written by the historians Ibn ʿAbd al-Ẓāhir (d. 1293) and his nephew Shāfiʿ ibn ʿAlī (d. 1330) and argues that these were in fact far more complex texts. An understanding of their discourses of legitimisation needs to be embedded within a broader understanding of the multi-directional discourses operating across the texts. The study proposes to interpret these texts as "spectacles", in which authors emplotted the reign of a sultan in thoroughly literary and rhetorical fashion, making especially extensive use of textual forms prevalent in the chancery. In doing so the authors reimagined the format of the biography as a performative vehicle for displaying their literary credentials and helping them negotiate positions in the chancery and the wider courtly orbit.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aIslam (7. Jh.). 4aKairo. 4aMuḥyī al-Dīn b. ʿAbd al-Ẓāhir. 4aShāfiʿ b. ʿAlī. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh  aHistoriography.  aIslamic history.  aMamluk.  asultanate.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z9783111318820oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107531340 cprintz978311075224340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311075302840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110753028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110753028/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  a978-3-11-131928-5  EBOOK PA